							<div class="post">I had used the transistors previously without base resistors in a different circuit, I must have fried them then.<br /><br />The sketch was just a simplified drawing of what I was trying to do (with a 390 ohm resistor to the base&nbsp; <img src="http://forum.arduino.cc/Smileys/arduinoWide/smiley-razz.png" alt="smiley-razz" border="0" />), you get the general idea, the transistors actually get their power from the same battery (about 10v) which powers the rest of the circuit, with the ground and +5v rails being connected to the arduino and anything else which requires 5 volts.<br /><br />The code should monitor the LDR for its value, if it&#039;s above the threshold value which is preset in the code, it starts incrementing a counter (counteropen), which once that goes above a certain value (delay1) it clicks the relay on which should power the motor so it can open a chicken coop door. The same applies in reverse. The delay is both for validation and to make sure the chickens would definitely be inside the coop when it closes.<br /><br />Make sense to you?<br /><br />Any more questions, feel free to ask <img src="http://forum.arduino.cc/Smileys/arduinoWide/smiley.png" alt="smiley" border="0" /></div>
